Problem Restatement ) leetcode 12)
Convert an integer n (1 â‰¤ n â‰¤ 3999) into its Roman numeral representation using the standard rules:

Symbols: I=1, V=5, X=10, L=50, C=100, D=500, M=1000.

Use subtractive forms for 4, 9, 40, 90, 400, 900.

Only I, X, C, M can repeat up to 3 times.

ðŸ§  Approach
Prepare a list of Roman numeral values and symbols in descending order, including subtractive forms:

Code
{1000, "M"}, {900, "CM"}, {500, "D"}, {400, "CD"},
{100, "C"}, {90, "XC"}, {50, "L"}, {40, "XL"},
{10, "X"}, {9, "IX"}, {5, "V"}, {4, "IV"}, {1, "I"}
For each value:

While n >= value, append the symbol to result and subtract value from n.

Continue until n = 0.

ðŸš€ GitHubâ€‘Ready C++ Code
cpp
#include <bits/stdc++.h>
using namespace std;

string intToRoman(int num) {
    vector<pair<int,string>> roman = {
        {1000,"M"}, {900,"CM"}, {500,"D"}, {400,"CD"},
        {100,"C"}, {90,"XC"}, {50,"L"}, {40,"XL"},
        {10,"X"}, {9,"IX"}, {5,"V"}, {4,"IV"}, {1,"I"}
    };
    
    string result;
    for (auto [val, sym] : roman) {
        while (num >= val) {
            result += sym;
            num -= val;
        }
    }
    return result;
}

int main() {
    ios::sync_with_stdio(false);
    cin.tie(nullptr);

    int T;
    cin >> T;
    while (T--) {
        int n;
        cin >> n;
        cout << intToRoman(n) << "\n";
    }
    return 0;
}
